2500|$|According to Laura Diane Kuhn, {{the heavier}} form of {{psychedelic}} <b>rock</b> known as <b>acid</b> <b>rock</b> {{developed from the}} late 1960s California music scene. Former Atlantic Records executive Phillip Rauls recalls: [...] "I was {{in the music business}} at the time, and my very first recognition of <b>acid</b> <b>rock</b> ... was, of all people, the Beach Boys and the song 'Good Vibrations'. ... That [...] sent so many musicians back to the studio to create this music on acid." [...] The Charlatans were among the first Bay Area <b>acid</b> <b>rock</b> bands, though Jefferson Airplane was the first Bay Area <b>acid</b> <b>rock</b> band to sign a major label and achieve mainstream success. By July 1967, Time magazine wrote, [...] "From jukeboxes and transistors across the nation pulses the turned-on sound of acid-rock groups: the Jefferson Airplane, the Doors, Moby Grape". In 1968, Life magazine referred to the Doors as the [...] "kings of acid rock".|$|R
